Did a successful prank inflate attendance expectations for President Trumpâs rally in Tulsa, Okla.?â£
â£
Trumpâs campaign promised huge crowds at his rally on Saturday - but it failed to deliver. While the presidentâs campaign had claimed that more than a million people had sought tickets for the rally, the 19,000-seat BOK Center was at least one-third empty during the event. A second outdoor venue was so sparsely attended that the president and Vice President Mike Pence both canceled appearances there.â£
â£
Hundreds of teenage TikTok users and fans of Korean pop music groups claimed to have registered potentially hundreds of thousands of tickets for Trumpâs campaign rally as a prank.â£
â£
After the Trump campaignâs official account posted a tweet asking supporters to register for free tickets using their phones on June 11, K-pop fan accounts began sharing the information with followers, encouraging them to register for the rally â and then not show. The trend quickly spread on TikTok, where videos with millions of views instructed viewers to do the same.â£
â£
Tap the link in our bio for more on how K-pop stans have been getting increasingly involved in American politics in recent months and the latest on Trumpâs rally in Tulsa. Photos by @nytmills.
